Italy has strengthened the tone towards NGO ships that rescue migrants.
Italy has warned NGOs owned by Mediterranean rescue ships that they will not be able to continue their work unless they comply with the new rules regulating their activities.
“If NGOs do not obey the new Code of Conduct, it’s hard to say whether they will be able to continue their activities,” Interior Minister Mario Minniti said in an interview with the Turkish daily newspaper Stampa.
The Minnesota warning came the next day after the Italian authorities confiscated a ship belonging to the German humanitarian organization "Jugend Rettet", suspected that its crew actually cooperates with human traffickers and facilitates illegal immigration.
The humanitarian organization, which has been working for a year, has refused to comment on the substance of detailed accusations against it by Italian prosecutor Ambrojo Cartozio.
“For us, the rescue of human lives is and will remain the highest priority, so we are very regret that we can’t continue our activities in the search and rescue zone now,” the organization said in a statement.
“We will be able to evaluate all the accusations presented now, only after we collect all the information and can evaluate the situation.”
The Italian authorities are monitoring the ship "Juventus", which belongs to "Jugend Rettet", from October.
His crew is suspected of taking the migrants on board with whole rescue boats, which human traffickers sent directly to them, and allowing the traffickers to leave along with the boats they could reuse.
At least one such meeting, as is expected, took place just 1.3 miles from the Libyan coast, according to the allegations, the content of which was published in Italian media.
The crew is suspected of violating the regulations of the Italian coastal authorities that control the rescue operations in the area, rather from humanitarian ruins than for any other reason.
The Code of Conduct implies, mainly, that the “Juventus” type vessels will have an Italian police officer on board to monitor their activities.
Until now, only three of the nine NGOs involved in search and rescue operations have agreed to obey the code: "Save Children", Maltese MOAS and "Pro-Activa Extended Arms" from Spain.
The latter said on Thursday that it considers the new rules unnecessary but acceptable provided they will not bring any "significant changes or interference" to its rescue operations.
Among those who refused to sign, there is the Nobel Prize-winning organization Doctors Without Borders (MSF).
Meanwhile, Miniti said that the sharp decline in the recent weeks in the number of migrants arriving in Italy as a result of rescue operations indicates that efforts to support the Libyan coastal guard and cooperation with the local mayor are bringing fruit.
“In the last days we have begun to see light at the end of the tunnel,” the minister said.
He plans for further negotiations with Libyan mayors on economic development initiatives and with Chad, Niger and Mali on measures to reduce the number of migrants leaving these countries in the hope of reaching Europe.
