The Russian authorities have recently significantly activated their policy in the Libyan direction, and with visits to Moscow participated delegations of the opposing Libyan parties.
The head of the Russian contact group on intra-Libyan settlement at the Foreign Ministry of the Russian Federation and the State Duma, the assistant head of the Czech Republic Lev Dengov told "Ъ", what objectives Moscow is pursuing in this region and on whom it makes a bet.
About the contact group in Libya you are leading, almost nothing is known.
Here, let’s say, the contact group in Ukraine – everyone knows about it.
Here is the curtain of the secret.
What exactly do you do, what goals are you pursuing?
The contact group was created on the initiative of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation and the State Duma.
Her activities are curated by Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs Mikhail Bogdanov and Adam Delimhanov (Duma Deputy from Chechnya. - "Ъ").
The latter is authorized to work in the Libyan direction by the Speaker of the State Duma, Vyacheslav Vladimir.
The key to the creation of the group was the arrest in Libya of the Russian tanker "Mehanik Chobotarev" (in September 2015, there were 11 people on board. - "Ъ").
We thought about how to help the crew.
Then a contact group was created from military specialists, representatives of the State Duma, our work was supported by the Chief of the Czech Republic Ramzan Kadyrov.
How did you find that you were the leader?
Since I have been working in Libya since 2008, I was asked to head the group.
Our activities were not limited to the release of sailors from the "Mechanika Chobotareva".
We managed to establish contacts with the representatives of all major groups opposing each other in the Libyan conflict - both from Tripoli (where the recognized UN government is based on the head of Faiz Sarajem. - "Ъ"), and with Tobruk (the residence of the parliament that opposes the government and supports Marshal Khalifa Haftar, who controls the eastern regions of Libya. - "Ъ").
Thanks to the active participation of Ahmed Metig (Libya’s Vice-Premier – “Ъ”), we managed to quickly agree on the release of Russian sailors.
Then it was decided to use these contacts more effectively, to create a contact group.
Its task is to analyze the situation, identify key factors and players, dialogue with all sides of the conflict.
I want to emphasize: in Libya we don’t want to associate with any of the sides of the conflict, we have dialogue with all.
How many people are in the contact group and how many of them are permanently in Libya?
There are currently five people in the contact group.
Among them are people who have experience working in force structures, including in the Ministry of Defense.
We also want to incorporate a group of specialists in the region, representatives of the Institute of the Middle East RAN.
There are no employees in Libya, and there is no need to do so.
There are now Russian military advisors and instructors in Libya.
If so, on whose side?
There are no Russian military specialists in Libya.
All conversations and publications about this are not true.
But in your contact group the former soldiers are ...
And their presence is necessary.
For example, when we visit hot points.
Or such closed to a certain point for us cities, such as Missurata (where the rebellion troops that played a role in the defeat of the Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi in 2011 and significantly activated in the subsequent years are based).
We arrived in Missouri in January of this year.
We were scared, they said that there were all Islamists, terrorists.
But it was important for us to evaluate the situation there, to analyze the real military potential, who is responsible for what, why such rumors go, what the role of Islamists is actually there.
In Missurate we met with all the representatives of the troops that were engaged in the destruction of the Islamic State in Sirte (in December 2016 this city on the Mediterranean coast was overturned by the militants of the prohibited Islamic State in Russia - "Ъ").
We wanted to look at them, to get acquainted with these people, to check the information that they played a decisive role in the destruction of the Islamic State in Libya, and not the Khalifa Haftar who attributed these merits to himself.
And what conclusion did you come to?
Is the “Islamic State” in Libya not defeated by Haftar?
This was not he doing.
Haftar conducted operations on the other front, in Benghazi.
And with the Islamic State in Sirte struggled structures who were subordinate to the government in Tripoli.
And, by the way, we invited people to Russia who conducted this anti-terrorist operation.
And they arrived - the visit lasted from 19 to 23 April of this year, the Libyan delegation was accepted in the Federation Council, in Duma, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Rosgvardi.
You, as we have understood, are in all the Libyan regions and probably imagine the mood of local elites and field leaders.
How do you think it will be possible to implement the ceasefire agreements, the elections reached at the end of July in Paris by Khalifa Haftar and Faiz Sarage?
Or again, as it has been repeatedly in the past, the agreements will be broken down, combat actions will be renewed, the parties will try to unilaterally take power?
For us a good signal has already been the fact that Sarage and Haftar agreed to another meeting, not so long ago it was impossible.
In the past, the two leaders have been extremely negative on each other.
As for Russia’s position...
They often write and say that Moscow actively supports Haftar, many believe in it.
We encountered this situation when they were in Misurat, and Haftar was on that day on board the Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Kuznetsov.
It was coincidence.
But in Missouri they did not believe in coincidence.
They told us, “You are probably very brave people who came to us right today.”
But our task is just to show: we do not only support Haftar, we do dialogue with all key parties in the conflict in Libya.
You talked with Haftar.
Does the mutual understanding with the Russian partners at the human, emotional level make it easier that he studied twice in the USSR?
And, by the way, does Haftar know the Russian language?
If you know Russian, it is relatively.
But what he learned from us, of course, facilitates dialogue with him.
And not only with him.
When we communicate with the military in Tripoli and Missouri, we meet the generals who have studied either in Russia or in the Soviet Union.
They speak well in Russian.
And they pull to Russia, somewhat experience nostalgia on it.
Do you think it is possible for the immediate abolition of the arms embargo on Libya?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in the supply of Russian weapons?
They are interested, of course, but, as I’ve said, we don’t take any side in this conflict and don’t want to arm one to the other.
We would like everyone to be in equal positions.
As for the arms embargo, there are constant calls from the Libyan people that Russia should somehow contribute to its withdrawal.
Currently, the process of drawing up the constitution is in progress in Libya.
We hope that the parties will come to a compromising solution and reach internal consensus.
Then elections should be held, as was stated at the meeting of Saraj and Haftar.
If the elections are held and the legitimate authority is finally elected (and now none of the parties has such status), then the UN Security Council can put the question of removing the arms embargo.
To raise this question is now meaningless and dangerous, it will only lead to the escalation of the conflict.
In recent days, the media that Italy, facing the problem of African refugees flying from Libya, feels arbitrarily abandoned by its EU allies.
Can Moscow in this situation help Italian partners by using its ties with the Libyan?
How realistic is, for example, the possibility that the Haftar troops will establish control over the coast and put an end to the business of the smugglers who send immigrants to Europe?
A very timely question.
We are actively working on this.
The Italians need the support of Russia, because Moscow is conducting dialogue simultaneously with Haftair, and with Sarajevo, and with Missouri and the south of the country.
