Michelle Carter sentenced for reports that led to Conrad Roy's suicide
A resident of Massachusetts was sentenced to two and a half years in prison for encouraging her boyfriend, Conrad Roy, to commit suicide through text messages and telephone calls.
Michelle Carter, who is now 20 years old, will have to spend 15 months of his deadline and another 5 years of trial.
Carter was convicted in June of the unintended murder of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy's father said at the hearing on Thursday: "My family was killed in the evil.
My son was my best friend.”
Carter was allowed to remain free until appeal.
She was threatened with a maximum period of 20 years, but her lawyers said that both she and Roy suffered mental disorders.
Carter, dressed in red pants and a cream bluz, listened to the judgment standing, pressing his hands and leaving his eyes.
“With her actions she killed Conrad Roy,” the prosecutor said.
She broke her life to improve her.
She did not recognize responsibility,” she said.
“She did not show regrets.”
But the lawyer Carter said it was "a tragic case that she deeply regrets."
However, judge Lawrence Monis said that, according to him, "her age, level of maturity or even a mental illness did not significantly affect her actions."
The prosecutor read the statements of Roy's mother, Lynn Roy, saying: "There has not been a day I would not complain about the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and the way I’m dealing with – I’m trying to support his sister despite all the pain that will remain with us forever.”
Roy's sister, Camden Roy, said she was irresponsibly pursued by the idea that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become the aunt of his children.
“To miss a person who has always been with me since I was born is a pain that will remain with me for the rest of my life,” she said.
This case seems to be a legal precedent, as in Massachusetts there is no law that would provide for the responsibility for the advice of a person to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in the car with symptoms of carbon gas poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The incident attracted the attention of the whole country when it became known that he was pushed to suicide by Carter's message.
"You can hang, jump from the roof, kill yourself with a knife I don't know there are many ways," she wrote in a few messages sent two weeks before his death when he rested with his family.
A few minutes before her suicide she wrote, “You have to do this, Conrad,” and “You just have to turn the fire into and you will be free and happy.”
Judge Monis said Carter wanted to get attention through the death of Roy, and banned her from communicating with the press in order to prevent her from getting what she wanted.
The opinions of the lawyers on this matter are divided.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Noks, who was sentenced in 2007 for killing her British neighbor in Italy by apartment and justified two years later.
The 30-year-old Nox published her special opinion in the Los Angeles Times, saying, “Michel Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prison.”
