Startups that will help your company not become another Uber
Amy Errett wanted to evaluate the level of satisfaction among the employees of her startup in the field of e-commerce, but the surveys did not work.
The answers were often widespread, useless, or worse, unrighteous.
And even though she promised anonymity, some employees did not trust this process.
“He’s never been consistent and objective,” said Errett, managing a 75-person company in San Francisco, Madison Reed, e-commerce in hair care.
He asked for help from third parties.
Now there is a new type of staff startups that help companies find out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software, the purpose of which is to measure the involvement of employees, they allow companies to make express queries, contact certain teams and demographic groups, offer employees anonymousness and hotline for complaints, and in some cases allow informers to pass the top management and contact directly to the management.
“We now have tools like Strava and Fitbit for health monitoring, and where is Fitbit for your company?” says Jim Barnet, co-founder and chairman of Glint from Redwood City, whose analytics programs are used by companies to measure the involvement of employees.
Errett said she has gained greater understanding of what her employees think and feel over the three years of using Glint.
In addition to express queries and questionnaires of certain teams, the product offers the company’s heat map and shows in a clear form which units have more complaints and which managers have a low approval rating, which allows it to understand why.
Companies gradually realize that they need to control the situation at work, otherwise they will become the next "Uber", who was involved in the scandal when a former employee posted a blog post in which he described an aggressive situation in which those who expressed dissatisfaction were punished.
For startups like “Glint”, the desire to control the situation is an opportunity for a profitable business.
According to the online portal "Let's Talk About Payment", dedicated to financial technologies, the global management, regulation and compliance industry could cost more than $118.7 billion by 2020.
The Convercent startup from Denver, Colorado, helping companies prevent and detect bad behavior, noted a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year in the background of Uber’s decline in reputation.
Convercent has 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
“Uber” has recently appeared among customers.
Like “Glint”, “Convercent” allows companies to send individually ordered staff opinion surveys, collect confidential real-time answers and view the heat maps of problem zones.
It also provides a hot line for anonymous text messages, which allows employees to report bad behavior.
And if the top manager is affected, the complaints go directly to the management.
“The public opinion court has taken over the authority of the inspectors,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If it turns out that the company is badly treating employees or behaving unethically, even if the inspector does not interfere, the company may face expensive consequences in the form of customers’ boycott, employees’ deflows and lawsuits, Quinlan said.
“Ruby Tuesday”, a restaurant network with more than 25,000 employees in 500 establishments, has used “Convercent” for more than a year to make sure that employees are aware of the rules and procedures, and to offer a simple way to contact the head office of the company.
Earlier, if the employee wanted to report the problem, he or she had to look for the telephone number or email of the head office, submit an official complaint and hope that it will be taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and unpleasant experience, said James Vitrano, head of the Ruby Tuesday company’s legal management, who said there was no normal way to track employees’ complaints.
Now that the company uses the Convercent service, the problems that were previously hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states – such as discrimination, harassment and unfair wages – can be discovered and dealt with faster.
“I can get closer to a comprehensive, comprehensive understanding of the situation of employees,” Vitrano, who leads the Ruby Tuesday risk management group, said.
“And we protect our shareholders from legal proceedings with employees.”
According to Quinland, the companies began to take ethics, values and employee involvement seriously in 2002, after the accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed due to ethical violations as a result of the Dale Enron.
But only when “social networks got mass spread,” companies realized that they won’t be able to keep their dirty clothes from viral spread on the net.
“Before starting to use technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy,” he said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service, taking regular fees from companies for the use of their products.
This is a business model and an opportunity that has been approved by venture investors who have supported both startups.
In February, Convercent received $10 million funding from companies such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, resulting in a total capital of $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, resulting in a total capital of $60 million.
These investments are unlikely to be surprising if we take into account the interconnected nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
The growing scale of research shows that today’s employees expect more jobs than before.
In markets with strong competition, such as Silicon Valley, high wages and interesting projects are just the necessary minimum.
Employees want to feel that they are accepted and appreciated, and that they spend their time on a company with a positive mission.
“When people are happy to work in a company, feel that they’re listening to them, and that the work they do brings results, they’re more trying to make such a company successful,” says Nina McQueen, Vice President for Global Benefits and Employee Satisfaction at LinkedIn, where both “Convercent” and “Glint” are used.
Investors get income when the company’s portfolio is going well; the company’s business is going well when employees are committed and engaged.
If third-party analytical tools promise to increase employees’ loyalty and involvement, it’s not surprising that they find support.
As culture experts say at work, it is important to have data about the involvement of employees.
But the data is useless until the guardians of the company take action.
In fact, if a company asks employees for feedback, it can make the impression that changes are going on.
And if the changes don’t happen quickly enough, or don’t happen at all, disappointment can develop, and employees lose interest.
“If you’re going to ask for 4,000 proposals, you’ll have to be ready to hold 4,000 conversations,” says Russell Rat, Chairman of Management Consultancy at Kotter International, who had to see how companies make a mistake by too much relying on data collection.
“Because if you don’t go to the end, the employees will think, ‘Do you really hear me?
You do not matter?
And if you don’t care, why should I don’t care?”
According to Errett, the company Madison Reed, which is now conducting monthly staff surveys, is able to take action on the same day when someone reports the problem with Glint.
And, after gathering feedback from employees, unhappy with the speed of decision making and the quality of communication, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve problems.
Ruby Tuesday is getting new knowledge about its employees and hopes that in the long run this knowledge will help it keep employees more efficiently in a industry known for its high staff flow.
“If you don’t try to create a culture of transparency, you’ll lose people,” Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose customers.
If you lose customers, you lose the company.
