I love the archives!”
For a person covered by such a passion for old papers, getting the support of the National Foundation and the English Art Council and living in the castle for four months ("Honestly, I've got a little down there") seems too good to be true.
Rhodes studied the “new” Victorian castle all the days, walked through archives and looked at numerous treasures of possessions and ancient things – for example, the heads of ginseng on the walls or bottles, centuries spent in ruin.
He walked through the park and through the ruins of the old castle, talked with foresters, gardeners and sometimes with the artists who worked on the illustrations of his book.
Then in the evening, he "dry whisky and sat down to write."
The history of the castle is not much studied because the National Fund received full access to it only in 2006, when the last inheritance, Elizabeth Hassy, died.
When Rhodes arrived there ten years later, the staff just began to deal with the archive, which he describes as "that the aristocrats have fallen down for centuries."
Diaries, letters from the time of the British Empire, maps showing who possessed something: “You think the land disputes are boring,” Rods says, “but here for this barge two families were fighting.
So is it, guys!”
In some stories, the castle is becoming the starting point for wider searches in English history: for example, in the "Worker", the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the 1381 village revolution.
“There are information about the rebellion that took place in the castle in 1380, in a book entitled ‘The Knights of Kent and Sasseks’,” Rods says.
“The peasant rebellion began in these places, and I thought that the rebellion was the right beginning.
Maybe they were connected?”
Other stories are closely linked to the history of the castle, for example, the Priest, which tells us about the Jesuit priest, whom the Darrell family had hidden for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or the "contrabandist", about the 18th-century contractor Arthur Darrell, who is believed to scan his own funeral, grabbing the tomb with stones (this was discovered a few years later when the tomb was excavated).
Darreli is Rhodes’ favorite family of all who lived in Scotney: “The gentlemen seemed to be a perfect jelly, they always went into debt and spent money on what they couldn’t afford.
In different generations, Darrella men have solved their debt problems by marrying wealthy older women – I imagine them as a company of sympathetic guys who know how to take care of the heirs of great wealth.”
After completing his work in the Castle, Rhodes is looking for other opportunities to gain a unique writer experience.
He lived for two weeks in a Finnish glush, where he wrote a graphic novel about Elayamanmiaki - a place where at the beginning of the 20th century was a sanatorium, and then it again grown into the forest.
But Scotney remains a special place for him.
“I was sad to leave,” he said.
“I felt like this: I’ve got to get back to real life again.”
