Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate can help relieve the inflammation.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent studies say the opposite: a diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help relieve symptoms in those suffering from inflammatory intestinal diseases.
This unhealing disease, which suffers about 1.3 million people in the U.S. and 300,000 in the UK, leads to colics and abdominal swelling, chronic or blood sweat, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Usually, to relieve symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy, but researchers from the Washington University have found that the main amino acid triptophan contributes to the production of immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
The leading researcher, Dr. Marco Colona, explained that the intestinal immune cells monitor that harmful microbes coming from food do not penetrate the body.
Cells capable of triggering the inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance, protecting the body and not harm sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too severe in the direction of inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory diseases of the intestine.
Experiments have shown that mice that have a certain bacteria in the intestine have increased cell tolerance.
And this bacteria needs tryptophan – one of the building elements of the protein – to trigger the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colona said: "We have established a connection between one type of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri, which is part of a normal intestinal microbiome, and the development of the population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more triptophan was contained in the mouse diet, the more these immune cells they had.
He suggested that the same will work in humans: a combination of L. reuteri and a triptophan-rich diet can contribute to a more tolerant and less inflammatory environment in the intestine.
Dr. Louise Cervantes-Barraganvas, studying the variety of increasing tolerance immune cells, found that one group of suspected mice had these cells, and the other group, which belonged to the same line but contained separately, did not have them.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by the intestinal microbioms of mice – the communities of bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of the mouse intestinal cells was sequentiated, and six types of bacteria were found present in mice with immune cells but absent in mice without them.
Mouse grown in a sterile environment, having no good microbioma and not developed this type of immune cells, received L. reuteri, and immune cells in them appeared.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grown L. reuteri in a liquid environment and then transferred small portions of liquid - without bacteria - to undeveloped immune cells separated from mice.
The immune cells are converted into cells that increase tolerance.
When the active component was separated from the liquid, it was a side product of triptophan processing, known as indol-3 milk acid.
When the researchers doubled the number of triptophan in the mouse food, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the level of triptophan was doubled, the number of cells also doubled.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that humans have the same increasing cell tolerance as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in their gastrointestinal tract.
It is unknown whether the L. reuteri triptophan side-products contribute to the development of cells in humans as well as in mice, but in people suffering from inflammatory intestinal diseases, defects in triptophan-related genes have been detected.
She says, “Maybe the development of these cells we need to strengthen, as the inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestines depend on these cells.
The high levels of triptophan with the presence of L. reuteri can potentially lead to the expansion of their population.”
