Revisit for the White House cost the taxpayers a thousand dollars
According to the records of the armed forces provided to Time, the White House's decision last month to bring a marine infantry helicopter to the South Loyal for an event dedicated to U.S. industrial production cost taxpayers $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as "Marine One", when the president is on board, became the central element of the event held on July 17 in the White House, on which the U.S. construction programs were demonstrated.
President Donald Trump, Vice-President Mike Pence and White House officials have reviewed technology products from all 50 states.
The helicopter, manufactured in Connecticut, was exposed next to a Yacht from Man, a Wisconsin fire car and a carrier from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Squad of Helicopters (HMX-1), the department responsible for controlling the helicopter, the Military Administration of the White House ordered the presence of the helicopter in a private order, or "FRAGO", just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Loyal in the event of a "unusual" event.
“I just wanted you to make sure you’re aware because it’s an unusual broad news event,” HMX-1 commander wrote in an e-mail to his chief, the first deputy chief of aviation of the Navy Corps, on the eve of the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter will arrive on the South Loyal at about 7 a.m. on July 17 to participate in the event intended for 3 hours of the day, and will remain there before the garden will be released between 6 and 9 a.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if the departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required for the return flight in accordance with the working hours restrictions.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event, and the guard staff remained next to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
From the records received by Time magazine, it remains unclear whether the second crew was eventually required.
The Hutch law prohibits federal officials from using state property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 clarified whether the event is not contrary to this ruling.
“In addition, we asked if it was not a violation of the Hatch law, and we were answered that no,” the commander wrote.
“It seems that you have no place to do,” the Deputy Chairman replied.
The "Made in America" event was declared by the White House as an official event, and the Hutch law did not apply to it.
But even official events have political notes.
During the event, the president made efforts to promote the health reform that was at the time in development in the Senate, and praised attempts to regulate government decrees.
The use of aircraft known as “Marine One” and “Air Force One” for political purposes is unlikely a new phenomenon.
The presidents are ordered to use them for travel.
But asking them only for the interests of photography is unusual.
Trump has already become the subject of discussions in February, when the presidential aircraft went on the backdrop during his first pre-election demonstration in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was overwhelmed by messages with complaints about the use of the presidential aircraft by his predecessor.
“The White House is excited about the ‘Made in America’ show, which showed products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials,” White House spokeswoman Lindsay Walters said.
The HMX-1 crews frequently carry out training flights around the Washington agglomeration and the South Lake to train the U.S. President's transportation to the White House with accuracy up to a inch.
When Trump was at the G20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 held 58 training landings at the White House.
According to one of the officials, the flight carried out for the event "Made in America" was counted to the crew as the necessary training flights for a month.
The unit’s helicopters on that day also flew 11 additional hours as part of “non-presidential support tasks.”
According to the White House, taxpayers did not cost any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A spokesman for Sikorsky said the company did not participate in the organization of a helicopter demonstration in the South Loyal.
HMX-1 does not take into account the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But according to the Ministry of Defense’s hourly rates for the 2017 fiscal year, the Ministry of Defense’s compensation rate for the VH-3D is $24,380 per hour of flight.
In the records of the unit is recorded that the aircraft was 30 minutes in each side of its airport based on the air base of the Quantico Navy in Virginia.
The White House claims that the actual cost of using a helicopter is much lower than that rate.
“To calculate the cost for taxpayers based on the example rate of compensation is completely wrong,” says Walters.
“These example rates include personal composition, service and many other irreversible costs that are included in annual assignments.”
According to a study conducted in 2015 by REND, the reimbursement rates do not include the cost of the individual, but actually take into account the cost of fuel, service and costs specified in the contract.
At the time, former White House spokesman Sean Spicer spoke about defending the use of a helicopter for the event.
“The idea is to demonstrate this week the things that have been done in America,” Spicer said.
“And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud that they are contributing to national security, and that there are, I guess, hundreds, if not thousands of people whose workplace depends on it.
And I think, like most Americans, we are all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have been constantly working on.
Therefore, of course, it is quite appropriate to pay this attention.”
It was unclear whether Trump was interacting with a helicopter, inspecting the South Stream during the event, but he was exactly sitting on the driver's place in a fire car.
Within the White House, Trump addressed Sikorsky’s representatives, kissing with the press on the topic of his own fleet of the company’s products.
“I know Sikorsky very well,” said the president, “I have three of them.”
